english:
  title: A Letter of Congratulations to Minister Pae Cheol upon His Return to the Court
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly read the imperial decree announcing that Your Excellency has ascended once more to the seat of honor. The radiance spreads across all the land, and all living beings rejoice beyond measure.

    What I celebrate today springs not from mere convention or ornamental phrases, but from the celestial blessing and fortune of our great nation. Yet my joy overflows, and praise demands expression. I dare present these words of commendation, hoping to convey my sincere devotion.

    I reflect upon Your Excellency: your virtue inherits the clarity of the ancients, your way draws from humility and restraint. You journeyed through the Central Kingdom and ascended to high office during the sacred travels of our enlightened ruler, witnessing the harmonious works of a worthy minister. Though family troubles once cast a shadow and you withdrew from the capital to distant provinces, soon you grasped again the reins of great affairs. Now Heaven itself seems to recant its sorrows, and each day brings us closer to peace. The sovereign has called upon your talents anew, restoring you to your former place—treading the path of Zhou's great general commanding armies, employing the stratagems of Jin's minister of commerce. The four quarters speak of this everywhere, and all hearts turn in unified celebration.

    I, unworthy though I am, have received your exceptional favor, and am ashamed of this kindness. Now that the great reckoning approaches again, my longing to serve grows fervent. Yet lacking the opportunity to express my gratitude, I can only offer these feelings, inadequate as they are.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a memorial letter (서, seo) written in the Tang-influenced style of the Silla period, addressed to Minister Pae Cheol upon his restoration to high office.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to 'Zhou's general' and 'Jin's minister' are classical allusions to capable administrators of ancient China, used here to praise the recipient's administrative prowess.
  - key: ''
    value: The author Choe Chi-won was a renowned Silla scholar-official and writer who frequently employed classical Chinese literary forms and allusions in his diplomatic and ceremonial correspondence.
